00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:04.290
And I'm going to start with
a piece called "Waiting

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:07.330
with the Gourd Moon",
that I wrote as a coda

00:08:07.330 --> 00:08:09.510
to Black History Month
for the New York Times.

00:08:09.510 --> 00:08:13.550
[ Paper Sounds ]

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:16.280
"'Waiting with the Gourd Moon.'

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:20.150
I dream of the world in
its existence before me.

00:08:20.150 --> 00:08:22.850
I am child shrinking
to white fetus,

00:08:22.850 --> 00:08:24.930
then minimized to a grain.

00:08:24.930 --> 00:08:27.260
Then I fold into nothingness.

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:30.150
And in this form, I lightly
trace the scars [inaudible]

00:08:30.150 --> 00:08:34.370
scraped into the god blue
back of the Atlantic,

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:38.040
until I find myself sitting
between a brown elder's legs,

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:41.400
while he tosses tails
up to a gourd moon.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:44.630
Market women [inaudible]
to a blossoming sun.

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:47.350
We stomp the ground
to night palpitations

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:53.100
from heavy height skid drums as
[inaudible] a plum purple sky.

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:57.180
The majesty of a village settles
upon me like the dust of stars.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:00.630
I sing out for my ancestors,
not knowing their names.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:02.750
I cry for them not
knowing the losses.

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:06.380
I dream of them not
knowing if they dream of me.

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:09.380
I inhale them, the
beads making the necks,

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:13.570
the vases crowning the skulls,
lips sliding open and welcome.

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:15.880
My sisters, I call to you.

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:19.410
My brothers, I ask of you,
toss your stories at me.

00:09:19.410 --> 00:09:22.260
Fling your love to me
with upturned lips.

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:23.980
Let me walk with you.

00:09:23.980 --> 00:09:25.460
Let me talk with you.

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:27.380
Let me watch when you laugh.

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:30.420
Hang back your head face
stretching up to the clouds

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:33.540
as if you're eating
the sweetest sunset.

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:37.810
Let me hear the brown grass sing
below while flames leap high.

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:40.890
Let me dance, dance with you
until the music cracks us

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:42.880
out of our bodies like nuts.

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:48.540
I want to come home to you, you
who sketch ancient brown rhythms

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:51.510
in my chest, you who drag
hieroglyphs with your feet

00:09:51.510 --> 00:09:54.240
and milk sands you,
who resurrect houses

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:56.910
and pharaohs while your
voice climbs the silver rungs

00:09:56.910 --> 00:10:00.180
of stars, you who wind
the Nile around my wrists

00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:03.980
and stretch my smile wide as
the Sahara, you who hum heritage

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:07.920
with the womb of flesh within
you, you who open your palm

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:11.580
like buckets, waiting
tenderly to receive me.

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:20.510
I am co, and we will be reborn
into a world without change,

00:10:20.510 --> 00:10:24.260
where redemption is
greater than Emancipation,

00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:26.530
where [inaudible] both
plump fruits swelling

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:31.510
from my people's laughter
in the glory of our roots."

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:37.380
[ Applause ]

00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:41.640
Great; and I'm going to read
a poem that I semi-apologize

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:43.600
because I know some of
you have heard it before.

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:47.100
It is the poem that I had the
honor to read as an introduction

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:49.990
to our current US Poet
Laureate Tracy K. Smith.

00:10:49.990 --> 00:10:55.770
And it's called "In This
Place (An American Lyric)".

00:10:55.770 --> 00:11:00.630
"There's a poem in this place
in the footfalls, and the halls,

00:11:00.630 --> 00:11:02.910
and the quiet beats
of the seats.

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:06.140
It is here at the curtain of day

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:10.230
where America writes a lyric
you must whisper to say.

00:11:10.230 --> 00:11:14.050
There's a poem in this place, in
the heavy grace, the lined face

00:11:14.050 --> 00:11:16.220
of this noble building
collections burned

00:11:16.220 --> 00:11:17.940
and were born twice.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:20.290
There's a poem in
Boston's Copley Square

00:11:20.290 --> 00:11:23.100
where protests chants tear
through the air like sheets

00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:27.660
of rain, where love of the many
swallows hatred of the few.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.710
There's a poem in
Charlottesville with tiki torch

00:11:30.710 --> 00:11:34.750
of string, a ring of flame
tight around the wrist of night,

00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:39.220
where men so white they
glean blue seen like statues

00:11:39.220 --> 00:11:42.490
where [inaudible] that long
wax burning ever higher,

00:11:42.490 --> 00:11:45.020
where heather higher
blooms forever

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:46.870
in a meadow of resistance.

00:11:46.870 --> 00:11:49.470
There's a poem at the
great sleeping giants

00:11:49.470 --> 00:11:52.780
of Lake Michigan defiantly
raising its big blue head

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:58.110
to Milwaukee and Chicago,
a poem begun long ago blaze

00:11:58.110 --> 00:12:00.810
into frozen soil
strutting upward and aglow.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:04.990
There's a poem in Florida,
in Puerto Rico, in East Texas

00:12:04.990 --> 00:12:07.190
where streets swell
into a nexus of rivers,

00:12:07.190 --> 00:12:11.350
cows afloat like modeled
buoys in the brown,

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:13.480
where courage is now so common

00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:17.210
that 23 year old Jesus Contreos
[phonetic] rescues senior

00:12:17.210 --> 00:12:19.690
citizens from floodwaters.

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:22.960
There's a poem in my Los
Angeles [inaudible] wide

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:26.220
as the Pacific tide where
a single mother swelters

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:28.740
in the windowless
classroom teaching black

00:12:28.740 --> 00:12:31.530
and brown students in Watts
to spell out their thoughts

00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:34.850
so her daughter write
like this poem for you.

00:12:34.850 --> 00:12:37.410
There's a lyric in
California where thousands

00:12:37.410 --> 00:12:40.560
of students march for blocks
and document it, and unafraid

00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:43.460
when my friend Rosa finds
the power to blossom

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:46.380
and deadlock her spirit, the
bedrock of her community.

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:49.880
She knows hope is like a
stubborn ship gripping a dock

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:53.560
of truth that you can't stop a
dreaming or knock down a dream.

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:58.220
How could this not be her
city, su nacion, our country,

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:03.440
our America or American lyric to
write to, a poem by the people,

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:07.400
the poor, the Protestants, the
Muslim, the Jew, the Native,

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:10.120
the immigrant, the black, the
brown, the blind, the brave,

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:13.420
the undocumented, and
undeterred, the woman, the man,

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:19.520
the albino, the trans, the ally
to all of the above and more.

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:22.430
Tyrants fear the poet.

00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:24.840
Now that we know it,
we can't blow it.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:28.060
We owe it to show it, not slow
it, although it hurts to sew it

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:30.630
when the world [inaudible] below
it, hope, we must bestow it

00:13:30.630 --> 00:13:33.800
like a wick in the poet
so it can grow, lit,

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:37.580
bringing with it new
stories to rewrite,

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:41.790
the story of a Texas city
depleted but not defeated,

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:44.400
a history written that
need not be repeated,

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:48.660
and nation composed,
but not yet completed.

00:13:48.660 --> 00:13:52.730
There's a poem in this
place, a poem in America,

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:55.810
a poet in every American
who rewrites this nation,

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:59.140
who tells a story worthy of
being told on this minnow

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:02.320
of an Earth to breathe, hope
into [inaudible] of time,

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:04.520
a poet to every American
who sees

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:07.150
that a poem penned
isn't a poet's end.

