I am the product of, 'Yes,
ma'am,' and, 'No ma'am,

00:28:16.510 --> 00:28:18.570
instead of 'Yeah, huh, what,

00:28:18.570 --> 00:28:20.570
weaving its way
into my vocabulary.

00:28:20.570 --> 00:28:22.890
And no matter where I
come from, and no matter

00:28:22.890 --> 00:28:24.330
where I was raised,

00:28:24.330 --> 00:28:29.340
I will always remember
Southern fresh soil

00:28:29.340 --> 00:28:30.860
or Southern slick city streets.

00:28:30.860 --> 00:28:35.510
It don't matter because I
was raised by the South."

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:43.940
[ Applause ]

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:48.990
This was one of my first
takes at a page poem,

00:28:48.990 --> 00:28:56.850
[laughs] which I discovered
to be really fun, actually.

00:28:56.850 --> 00:29:03.210
"Bystanders are streetlights
that watch headlights kiss,

00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:06.680
crashing lips as life stops.

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:11.620
They are the closets that hold
tangled purple and blue limbs,

00:29:11.620 --> 00:29:17.190
breath that rips from lungs, and
salty cheeks that caress paint.

00:29:17.190 --> 00:29:19.870
They are the toilets
that carry dry heaves,

00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:23.700
like the lock hugs the
refrigerator and the cabinets.

00:29:23.700 --> 00:29:26.550
They are the drawer
that cradles the belt.

00:29:26.550 --> 00:29:28.740
They are the eyelids
that never shut.

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:33.060
They are the journals that
hold poems of everything,

00:29:33.060 --> 00:29:36.710
of everything, and
never, ever tell.

00:29:36.710 --> 00:29:39.280
They are window seals
that don't breathe.

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:41.630
They are doors that don't eat.

00:29:41.630 --> 00:29:45.080
They are jeans that
lay against red lines

00:29:45.080 --> 00:29:50.830
and never dye their color,
never dip into the irises

00:29:50.830 --> 00:29:56.010
of haunted eyes, too scared the
poltergeist might follow them

00:29:56.010 --> 00:30:01.470
home, might crack open
their jaw if their lips,

00:30:01.470 --> 00:30:09.310
it will become nightmare.

00:30:09.310 --> 00:30:20.830
Bystanders are death, they are
mute, they are streetlights

00:30:20.830 --> 00:30:32.240
that never, ever blink."

00:30:39.510 --> 00:30:48.450
[ Applause ]

00:30:48.450 --> 00:30:49.940
&gt;&gt; William Lohier: Hi, everyone.

00:30:49.940 --> 00:30:51.240
&gt;&gt; Hey.

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:53.050
&gt;&gt; William Lohier: I just
want to say I'm so honored

00:30:53.050 --> 00:30:56.630
and privileged to have the
opportunity to be able to speak

00:30:56.630 --> 00:30:58.520
to a roomful of people.

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:01.200
And I think especially now
in the time that we live

00:31:01.200 --> 00:31:03.510
in providing this platform

00:31:03.510 --> 00:31:07.510
for young people is
more important than ev

00:31:07.510 --> 00:31:12.240
[ Applause ]

00:31:12.240 --> 00:31:15.220
And this is a poem that
I wrote in response

00:31:15.220 --> 00:31:21.640
to yesterday's walkout
by high school students.

00:31:21.640 --> 00:31:25.930
"Yesterday, one month after the
deadliest high school shooting

00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:30.000
in American history, students
across the country marched

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
for stricter gun laws.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.370
The same day, after suing
the state of Florida

00:31:35.370 --> 00:31:37.520
for raising the age
to buy assault rifles,

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:42.530
the NRA's Twitter account ,
'I'll control my own guns.

00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:43.960
Thank you.'

00:31:43.960 --> 00:31:48.990
And the question becomes,
'Why do we march?'

00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:52.470
When school shootings have
become an American promise,

00:31:52.470 --> 00:31:55.270
when the Second Amendment
[inaudible] bullets into bodies.

00:31:55.270 --> 00:31:58.050
We were not taught that
students could become soldiers

00:31:58.050 --> 00:31:59.810
at any time.

00:31:59.810 --> 00:32:02.660
A well-regulated militia being
necessary to the security

00:32:02.660 --> 00:32:05.070
of a free state, the right
of the people to keep

00:32:05.070 --> 00:32:07.670
and bear arms shall
not be infringed.

00:32:07.670 --> 00:32:12.810
We march because those words
are worth more than our lives,

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:16.210
because those who defend
them do not know our names,

00:32:16.210 --> 00:32:19.450
how our mommas know to hold
us close when pistols rejoice

00:32:19.450 --> 00:32:21.980
in the night like
martyrdom is the best some

00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:24.160
of us can expect in life.

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:25.840
We march because.

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:31.570
Because the other day,
we had a lockdown drill,

00:32:31.570 --> 00:32:33.870
and as my back was pressed
against the wall away

00:32:33.870 --> 00:32:37.170
from the window, I was
waiting for shots to ring out,

00:32:37.170 --> 00:32:38.710
blunt like the promise

00:32:38.710 --> 00:32:41.660
of freedom the way
politicians take NRA money

00:32:41.660 --> 00:32:43.370
and give us back bodies.

00:32:43.370 --> 00:32:46.590
We were not taught
the sound of gunshots.

00:32:46.590 --> 00:32:50.250
We have never been
asked to write eulogy.

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:54.760
We march because as I write
this poem, I want to be worrying

00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:58.330
about tests, and homework,
and acne, and grades,

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:02.300
and it's frustrating that
this poem sounds like an ode

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:05.670
to assault rifles, that my
grandmother prayed I would

00:33:05.670 --> 00:33:07.980
survive in case of
a school shooting,

00:33:07.980 --> 00:33:10.760
that an Austin sixth grader
wrote his will in case

00:33:10.760 --> 00:33:12.570
of a school shooting,
that 'in case

00:33:12.570 --> 00:33:17.240
of a school shooting' has
become a justification,

00:33:17.240 --> 00:33:21.120
but not justification
enough for stricter gun laws

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:23.840
because someone, someone

00:33:23.840 --> 00:33:27.290
in America says they
love their guns.

00:33:27.290 --> 00:33:34.520
And my body becomes a canvas,
becomes a false prophecy,

00:33:34.520 --> 00:33:40.100
and I flash back to police
siren, to red, white, blue, red,

00:33:40.100 --> 00:33:43.130
white blue, and I say in my
head over and over again,

00:33:43.130 --> 00:33:46.590
'Hands up, don't shoot.

00:33:46.590 --> 00:33:51.070
Hands up, don't shoot.'

00:33:51.070 --> 00:33:54.670
We march because I learned
long before high school

00:33:54.670 --> 00:34:01.150
to fear bullets, before
Columbine, before Sandy Hook,

00:34:01.150 --> 00:34:02.500
before Stoneman Douglas.

00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:06.130
We march because
today, I did not die.

00:34:06.130 --> 00:34:10.360
Today, I was not shot, not
crucified, not martyred,

00:34:10.360 --> 00:34:15.190
not made poster, or hashtag
'not afraid', didn't crouch

00:34:15.190 --> 00:34:17.090
down on my classroom today.

00:34:17.090 --> 00:34:21.770
Today, I didn't have to run,
or hide, or mourn a friend.

00:34:21.770 --> 00:34:25.820
We march because
today, I knew that one

00:34:25.820 --> 00:34:29.070
of those things could
happen at any time.

00:34:29.070 --> 00:34:30.610
They've happened before.

00:34:30.610 --> 00:34:32.830
We are not marching
to take your guns.

00:34:32.830 --> 00:34:37.160
We are marching for our lives.

00:34:37.160 --> 00:34:41.950
So watch us because there
is power in our footst.

00:34:41.950 --> 00:34:50.510
And the streets will ring with
it long after we are gone."

00:34:50.510 --> 00:35:00.420
[ Applause ]

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:04.600
And this second poem
I wrote for my dad,

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:08.610
and it's called "I
See Mountains."

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:11.910
"I watch as the white woman
won't sit next to my dad

00:35:11.910 --> 00:35:14.390
in the subway, won't be seen

00:35:14.390 --> 00:35:18.460
in the space a black man has
left behind, won't be possessed

00:35:18.460 --> 00:35:20.160
by the ghosts he
carries with him.

00:35:20.160 --> 00:35:22.940
She scans the car
for another seat,

00:35:22.940 --> 00:35:27.990
one with fewer nooses attached,
looking everywhere but at him,

00:35:27.990 --> 00:35:31.470
everywhere but at the empty
seat next to him that beckons

00:35:31.470 --> 00:35:35.540
with open arms, ignoring it
as if it were white privilege,

00:35:35.540 --> 00:35:37.180
as if it were unclean,

00:35:37.180 --> 00:35:43.090
as if there was ever could
sit while a white woman stood.

00:35:43.090 --> 00:35:45.860
I wonder if she is
suddenly aware

00:35:45.860 --> 00:35:47.880
of her whiteness the
same way I am aware

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:51.710
of my father's blackness;
how he carries space

00:35:51.710 --> 00:35:56.750
with him anywhere he goes,
a well so full of blood,

00:35:56.750 --> 00:35:59.150
and light, and magic,
and everything black

00:35:59.150 --> 00:36:00.570
that it is overflowed.

00:36:00.570 --> 00:36:03.440
How dirty he must feel
contaminating the seats next

00:36:03.440 --> 00:36:07.580
to him, his pride
planting explosives

00:36:07.580 --> 00:36:09.480
in the orange plastic skin

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:14.120
so bright it requires a
three-foot radius tongue a

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:19.000
skyscraper that could
collapse at any moment.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.770
And I think she must
recognize the risks associated

00:36:22.770 --> 00:36:26.640
with the air around his
body, how fragile it is,

00:36:26.640 --> 00:36:29.670
how precious breath is
in a black man's lungs.

00:36:29.670 --> 00:36:31.690
She stands with the
seat in front of her

00:36:31.690 --> 00:36:35.640
as I watch standing next to
her, and I want her to sit

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:37.550
to cast aside the fire hoses

00:36:37.550 --> 00:36:39.920
and German shepherds
her mind has rejected.

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:43.250
I want her to recognize that
when she ignores this seat,

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:46.020
she ignores The Promised Land.

00:36:46.020 --> 00:36:53.000
I want her to see my dad the way
I see him, as holy, as human,

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:55.690
as strong as he is fragile.

00:36:55.690 --> 00:37:04.100
And she smiles, reads her
book, continues to stand

00:37:04.100 --> 00:37:06.570
like George Wallace at
the schoolhouse door.

00:37:06.570 --> 00:37:11.660
And my dad winks at me
as if he sees the miracle

00:37:11.660 --> 00:37:15.600
in what has just occurred,
that a white woman gives

00:37:15.600 --> 00:37:20.120
up her birthright,
stands for a black man,

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:22.690
recognizes that he
takes up so much space

00:37:22.690 --> 00:37:29.460
in this world she
cannot possibly find room

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:30.940
to disrespect it.

00:37:30.940 --> 00:37:35.400
And I do no; bright
as the mountaintop

00:37:35.400 --> 00:37:44.570
where no trees can
grow, only flowers,

00:37:44.570 --> 00:37:47.560
that only black men
have ever set foot on.

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:52.330
So I think my father
moves mountains with him,

00:37:52.330 --> 00:37:56.590
has climbed them, tamed them.

00:37:56.590 --> 00:38:04.470
And he will sit for now enjoying
the space that he has earned."

00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:06.510
Thank you.

00:38:06.510 --> 00:38:17.040
[ Applause ]

