00:43:16.100 --> 00:43:18.780
So before I get into it, just to
give you a little bit of history

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:21.420
about the program; this
program was started

00:43:21.420 --> 00:43:25.250
in 2008 in New York City.

00:43:25.250 --> 00:43:29.190
And the idea behind it was
that young people had spaces

00:43:29.190 --> 00:43:32.420
like the [inaudible] and poets
cafes, the Apollo theaters

00:43:32.420 --> 00:43:36.380
of the world, and young people
were doing powerful, creative,

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:40.450
politically charged,
and important work.

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:44.150
And the idea was that we wanted
these young people to be able

00:43:44.150 --> 00:43:49.070
to be in spaces that they
were not traditionally offered

00:43:49.070 --> 00:43:50.370
access to.

00:43:50.370 --> 00:43:54.430
So when we envisioned where we
wanted these young people to be,

00:43:54.430 --> 00:43:58.740
it was originally like City
Hall, and it was a vision

00:43:58.740 --> 00:44:02.330
that really helped us
create a program that wanted

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:05.280
to celebrate young people that
were not only great poets,

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:08.320
but great leaders that were
interested in social justice

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:11.720
and social impact, that were
interested in civic engagement

00:44:11.720 --> 00:44:13.470
and really working
in their communities.

00:44:13.470 --> 00:44:16.030
So that's the model
by which we use

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:17.970
as the framework
for this program.

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:20.700
So everyone that you see here
tonight, as you could tell

00:44:20.700 --> 00:44:22.210
from their bios, along

00:44:22.210 --> 00:44:24.360
with being incredible artists
is an incredible leader;

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:26.150
they've done so much.

00:44:26.150 --> 00:44:31.300
Fast forward to about four
years ago, we got a new mayor

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:34.150
in New York City and his
name is Bill de Blasio.

00:44:34.150 --> 00:44:36.840
And we had the incredible
opportunity

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:39.040
where the Youth Poet Laureate
at the time of New York City,

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:42.620
Romney Romana [phonetic],
was invited to speak at --

00:44:42.620 --> 00:44:44.650
perform a poem that she
wrote for that event

00:44:44.650 --> 00:44:47.070
at de Blasio's inauguration.

00:44:47.070 --> 00:44:49.260
So it was an incredible moment

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:51.260
because there was only a
few people asked to speak;

00:44:51.260 --> 00:44:56.190
it was her, and Harry
Belafonte, and Bill Clinton.

00:44:56.190 --> 00:44:58.890
And [laughter] she
stole the show.

00:44:58.890 --> 00:45:00.490
The New York Times
wrote about it.

00:45:00.490 --> 00:45:04.030
And we -- there was
a lot of press.

00:45:04.030 --> 00:45:06.930
After that a lot of our partner
organizations were in a network

00:45:06.930 --> 00:45:09.790
of probably 60-plus
organizations that do this work

00:45:09.790 --> 00:45:11.420
in their communities,
and they wanted

00:45:11.420 --> 00:45:12.820
to know how they
could replicate that.

00:45:12.820 --> 00:45:15.040
And we actually have
folks from DC, Words Beats

00:45:15.040 --> 00:45:16.340
and Life here tonight

00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:18.700
that hosted the DC
Poet Laureate Program.

00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:22.640
So we decided that we wanted
to make this program something

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:24.820
that we could launch
in different cities.

00:45:24.820 --> 00:45:29.240
A few years ago at the twilight
of the Obama administration,

00:45:29.240 --> 00:45:34.680
we were invited to the White
House to meet Michelle Obama.

00:45:34.680 --> 00:45:37.030
And it was an incredible
opportunity, but what had

00:45:37.030 --> 00:45:39.390
to happen was that we
needed five finalists.

00:45:39.390 --> 00:45:42.290
We needed to kind of
get this local program

00:45:42.290 --> 00:45:45.340
that had city youth poet
laureates across the country

00:45:45.340 --> 00:45:47.810
to something where we were
going to sort of matriculate it

00:45:47.810 --> 00:45:50.170
up to a national
Youth Poet Laureate.

00:45:50.170 --> 00:45:53.330
So we quickly hustled
together all of our efforts,

00:45:53.330 --> 00:45:57.540
we named our inaugural group of
five finalists, and got to go

00:45:57.540 --> 00:46:00.630
to the White House; and, you
know, the rest is history.

00:46:00.630 --> 00:46:03.210
This past April, Amanda
was awarded the title

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:05.440
of the first national
Youth poet laureate.

00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:08.850
And now we have our first
set of new finalists

00:46:08.850 --> 00:46:10.780
for the second Youth
Poet Laureate.

00:46:10.780 --> 00:46:12.150
So it's been an incredible
journey

00:46:12.150 --> 00:46:14.690
that gives you a little
backdrop of the program.

00:46:14.690 --> 00:46:16.620
I want to get into
the conversation.

00:46:16.620 --> 00:46:19.200
Let's -- I want to start --

00:46:19.200 --> 00:46:21.050
yes I'll have a question
for everybody,

00:46:21.050 --> 00:46:22.640
and then prepare your
questions because I want

00:46:22.640 --> 00:46:24.240
to open it up to the audience.

00:46:24.240 --> 00:46:27.300
So I want to start
with Patricia,

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:32.010
