00:46:34.400 --> 00:46:36.650
I love your poem
about the Windy City.

00:46:36.650 --> 00:46:39.900
And right now Chicago, you
know -- it's been for a while,

00:46:39.900 --> 00:46:44.790
but the art that's coming out of
Chicago, the poetry, the music,

00:46:44.790 --> 00:46:48.670
the theater, it's, you know,
in my opinion, probably one

00:46:48.670 --> 00:46:52.340
of the most culturally
artistically vibrant cities,

00:46:52.340 --> 00:46:55.110
even politically active
cities that we have.

00:46:55.110 --> 00:46:57.240
It's really a touchstone
for, you know,

00:46:57.240 --> 00:47:00.530
what we should be doing in
terms of art and politics.

00:47:00.530 --> 00:47:02.490
And I just want to
know how that city

00:47:02.490 --> 00:47:04.900
and that scene inspires
you and your work.

00:47:04.900 --> 00:47:07.360
Do you feel supported
by it, or are you sort

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:10.090
of rogue doing this
incredible art on your own?

00:47:10.090 --> 00:47:11.860
So tell us a little
bit more about that.

00:47:11.860 --> 00:47:15.620
&gt;&gt; Patricia Frazier: Definitely
more supported than rogue.

00:47:15.620 --> 00:47:18.590
[Laughter] I think that
growing up in Chicago has kind

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:22.390
of been bittersweet, because
for so long growing up I had

00:47:22.390 --> 00:47:25.550
to watch people on the TV screen
tell me about the neighborhood

00:47:25.550 --> 00:47:27.150
that I lived in, and
the neighborhoods

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:28.450
that my friends lived in.

00:47:28.450 --> 00:47:33.580
And I think a long time we spent
asking politicians and our mayor

00:47:33.580 --> 00:47:36.030
to do the work of repairing
the image of the city,

00:47:36.030 --> 00:47:38.730
but after a while we just
kind of realized that this is

00:47:38.730 --> 00:47:40.420
of people's resistance;
this isn't going

00:47:40.420 --> 00:47:42.590
to work without the people.

00:47:42.590 --> 00:47:45.590
So a lot of our work, and
a lot of my work is kind

00:47:45.590 --> 00:47:49.310
of based upon disproving
narratives that are said

00:47:49.310 --> 00:47:53.650
about us, and not exactly
counteracting them,

00:47:53.650 --> 00:47:55.820
because like the thing about
stereotypes is they are true,

00:47:55.820 --> 00:47:57.140
right, like some of
these things are true,

00:47:57.140 --> 00:47:58.970
Chicago does have
a violence problem,

00:47:58.970 --> 00:48:00.640
Chicago does have a
gun violence problem,

00:48:00.640 --> 00:48:03.930
but also Chicago is
so many other things.

00:48:03.930 --> 00:48:07.600
So I think I'm just constantly
inspired by the people that I'm

00:48:07.600 --> 00:48:11.410
so lucky to work
with, especially more

00:48:11.410 --> 00:48:13.810
in the political
campaigning of things.

00:48:13.810 --> 00:48:15.630
I work with this group
called "Assada's Daughters",

00:48:15.630 --> 00:48:18.010
and where Assada's
Daughters is different

00:48:18.010 --> 00:48:20.930
from other organizations
is normally --

00:48:20.930 --> 00:48:22.230
and organizations

00:48:22.230 --> 00:48:25.500
that politically organize they
take what I like to call like

00:48:25.500 --> 00:48:28.260
"pretty diversity", you know,
black people that look good

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:30.710
on a poster board, black people
that look good on a podium.

00:48:30.710 --> 00:48:33.760
And Assada's takes kids
out of the neighborhood,

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:35.980
which is Washington Park, and
teaches them how to organize,

00:48:35.980 --> 00:48:37.620
and teaches them how to
speak up for themselves.

00:48:37.620 --> 00:48:39.380
Because sometimes
the person who needs

00:48:39.380 --> 00:48:42.390
to be speaking doesn't always
look like, you know, one of us.

00:48:42.390 --> 00:48:45.200
Sometimes it looks like my uncle
who has a felony and who listens

00:48:45.200 --> 00:48:47.450
to Gucci Mane, and
does all these

00:48:47.450 --> 00:48:48.880
like different things, right?

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:50.250
Those stories matter, too.

00:48:50.250 --> 00:48:52.310
So that's what I try to do, I
try to write about those people

00:48:52.310 --> 00:48:54.890
because they're more
important than the narrative

00:48:54.890 --> 00:48:58.140
that is being shown of Chicago.

00:48:58.140 --> 00:48:59.440
&gt;&gt; Wow.

