00:56:21.280 --> 00:56:23.290
that they submit a
poetry portfolio,

00:56:23.290 --> 00:56:25.210
but they also submit a CV.

00:56:25.210 --> 00:56:29.190
And that sort of ouir
social justice work,

00:56:29.190 --> 00:56:32.180
their organizational work, their
schoolwork, their accolades.

00:56:32.180 --> 00:56:36.860
And it seemed -- what's really
amazing to me is Los Angeles,

00:56:36.860 --> 00:56:41.460
of all places, which is so huge
and spread out and everything,

00:56:41.460 --> 00:56:43.850
is a chore to get
somewhere in Los Angeles

00:56:43.850 --> 00:56:46.840
because I spent a lot of time
on the West coast and LA myself;

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:49.430
everything is a hassle
to get anywhere.

00:56:49.430 --> 00:56:54.790
But at the same time, the
CVs from the kids in LA are

00:56:54.790 --> 00:56:58.400
like ridiculous, yours included.

00:56:58.400 --> 00:57:03.370
So and that says a lot about,
you know, parents, resources,

00:57:03.370 --> 00:57:06.140
what's going on in these
communities, kids having to go

00:57:06.140 --> 00:57:09.950
to places to do things in LA,
you have to make a real effort.

00:57:09.950 --> 00:57:15.670
And I want to know sort of the
intersection between, you know,

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:17.770
the efforts that you've made
in your life to do things

00:57:17.770 --> 00:57:19.680
and be a part of all of
these incredible groups

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:21.760
that you're proud
of and, you know,

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:23.210
connecting it with your work.

00:57:23.210 --> 00:57:24.750
Does one drive the other?

00:57:24.750 --> 00:57:28.790
You know, explain that synergy
between yourself as a poet,

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:32.650
and yourself as a person that's
just really involved in a lot

00:57:32.650 --> 00:57:35.820
of stuff in the community.

00:57:35.820 --> 00:57:37.360
&gt;&gt; Milla Kudas: For one thing,

00:57:37.360 --> 00:57:41.570
I think that Los Angeles
Public Transit does all right.

00:57:42.770 --> 00:57:45.160
[Laughter] Maybe not the
best, I'll give it that,

00:57:45.160 --> 00:57:47.400
but it does do all right.

00:57:47.400 --> 00:57:50.410
And I think also I had some
really, really great friends

00:57:50.410 --> 00:57:52.730
in high school -- because I'm
currently living right outside

00:57:52.730 --> 00:57:55.180
of Boston, and I go
to Wellesley College.

00:57:55.180 --> 00:57:59.270
But when I was in Los Angeles, I
did have some wonderful friends.

00:57:59.270 --> 00:58:02.400
And like the one person in the
friend group who did have a car

00:58:02.400 --> 00:58:05.260
and did drive was also really
passionate about poetry,

00:58:05.260 --> 00:58:06.940
and so certain missions
that we both really cared

00:58:06.940 --> 00:58:08.340
about we'd go together.

00:58:08.340 --> 00:58:12.430
But I think as far as the
intersection between my work

00:58:12.430 --> 00:58:14.920
and also like my work in
communities, I think they're one

00:58:14.920 --> 00:58:16.640
in the same in a lot of ways.

00:58:16.640 --> 00:58:18.430
And it goes back to
what Cassidy was sayi,

00:58:18.430 --> 00:58:21.020
the idea that sometimes
when I'm saying a poem,

00:58:21.020 --> 00:58:23.490
when someone comes up to me
and says like, "I needed that,"

00:58:23.490 --> 00:58:25.130
that feels like I'm
doing the work.

00:58:25.130 --> 00:58:27.340
But I think that's
always not enough.

00:58:27.340 --> 00:58:29.340
Sometimes that's emotional
labor and that's work,

00:58:29.340 --> 00:58:31.000
but you also have
to go So I'm part

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:33.170
of Young People Creating Change.

00:58:33.170 --> 00:58:37.080
And like we put on open mic

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:40.590
so that we're not
always the only people

00:58:40.590 --> 00:58:41.890
up there saying things.

00:58:41.890 --> 00:58:44.510
We want to invite other youth
to tell their stories as well.

00:58:44.510 --> 00:58:46.950
And I think when you're so
passionate and when poetry kind

00:58:46.950 --> 00:58:49.010
of consumes your life,
it just doesn't stop,

00:58:49.010 --> 00:58:50.440
and it's a beautiful,
wonderful thing

00:58:50.440 --> 00:58:52.420
that I would never, ever change.

00:58:52.420 --> 00:58:57.290
So it doesn't feel like a lot
until like you check your watch

00:58:57.290 --> 00:58:58.950
and it's like 10:00 and
you realize you haven't

00:58:58.950 --> 00:59:01.430
like drank water, because you've
been just like going everywhere

00:59:01.430 --> 00:59:02.730
and you've been on the train.

00:59:02.730 --> 00:59:05.740
But then you have friends and
support systems around you

00:59:05.740 --> 00:59:10.820
who make drinking water a
think you are reminded of.

00:59:10.820 --> 00:59:14.310
So yes that's all
I've got to say.

00:59:14.310 --> 00:59:16.110
&gt;&gt; Michael Cirelli:
Awesome, awesome, cool.

00:59:16.110 --> 00:59:21.040
[ Applause ]

00:59:21.040 --> 00:59:25.100
Awesome; and I'll be asking a
more poetry-related question

00:59:25.100 --> 00:59:26.400
for Rukmini.

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:31.050
What I really love about your
work is that whether it's a poem

00:59:31.050 --> 00:59:36.970
about Houston, or a poem
about a city in India,

00:59:36.970 --> 00:59:39.170
it sounds like it could
be in the same place.

00:59:39.170 --> 00:59:42.890
You know, and that's a real
skill as a poet and an artist

00:59:42.890 --> 00:59:45.340
to be able to have
such a definitive voice

00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:48.190
that anything you're talking
about feels like it's coming

00:59:48.190 --> 00:59:50.380
from the one singular
voice of the poet.

00:59:50.380 --> 00:59:54.650
So I wanted you to explain a
little bit how you managed to do

00:59:54.650 --> 00:59:59.770
that incredible feat of talking
about family, background,

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:08.450
Houston, Texas, being
-Harvey, so and how you melt

01:00:08.450 --> 01:00:13.100
that into a singular poetic
voice that has that consistency

01:00:13.100 --> 01:00:15.260
that I love about your work.

01:00:15.260 --> 01:00:16.560
&gt;&gt; Rukmini Kalamangalam: Sure.

01:00:16.560 --> 01:00:19.230
I think one thing that really
informs it is that I am

01:00:19.230 --> 01:00:21.730
that singular being, right,
there are so many things

01:00:21.730 --> 01:00:24.630
that are incorporated in my
life because we've moved a lot.

01:00:24.630 --> 01:00:29.100
So I was born in the UK, I grew
up for six years in Scotland,

01:00:29.100 --> 01:00:31.520
and then, you know, we
moved to the United States.

01:00:31.520 --> 01:00:34.520
And there's always been
this sense of like --

01:00:34.520 --> 01:00:36.710
you know, my parents always
tried to instill in me the sense

01:00:36.710 --> 01:00:40.550
that I'm a global citizen, and
that it's my responsibility

01:00:40.550 --> 01:00:42.920
to not only speak out for
the places that I'm from,

01:00:42.920 --> 01:00:45.460
and the places that I'm living
in, but also all the places

01:00:45.460 --> 01:00:47.520
that I am connected to.

01:00:47.520 --> 01:00:50.460
And so I think that
I've been trying

01:00:50.460 --> 01:00:53.940
to explain myself
for a very long time.

01:00:53.940 --> 01:00:56.900
And that's where the voice comes
from, I think, is this idea

01:00:56.900 --> 01:01:00.290
that I am a whole bunch of
different things, but primarily,

01:01:00.290 --> 01:01:02.400
people see me as
Indian-American.

01:01:02.400 --> 01:01:05.770
And you know, the idea that
I've often been, you know,

01:01:05.770 --> 01:01:08.020
the only Indian-American,
the only Asian-American,

01:01:08.020 --> 01:01:10.390
so you're always trying to
speak up for that voice.

01:01:10.390 --> 01:01:12.830
But at the same time, you
know, you're a diverse person,

01:01:12.830 --> 01:01:14.450
you have varied interests,

01:01:14.450 --> 01:01:16.360
and you encompass a lot
of different things.

01:01:16.360 --> 01:01:19.180
And so for me, it's the
idea that my identity

01:01:19.180 --> 01:01:22.670
as a global citizen, as a
person of many cultures,

01:01:22.670 --> 01:01:25.990
informs my beliefs on a
lot of different issues.

01:01:25.990 --> 01:01:28.330
So I try to bring that
part of me to everything

01:01:28.330 --> 01:01:29.740
that I said on the page.

01:01:29.740 --> 01:01:31.540
&gt;&gt; Michael Cirelli:
Awesome; thank you.

01:01:31.540 --> 01:01:35.500
[ Applause ]

01:01:35.500 --> 01:01:37.340
Thanks. A question for Amanda.

01:01:37.340 --> 01:01:38.640
&gt;&gt; Amanda Gorman:
No; I don't want

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:39.970
to go, they've done so well.

01:01:39.970 --> 01:01:41.270
[Laughter]

01:01:41.270 --> 01:01:42.570
&gt;&gt; Michael Cirelli: There
are so many I can ask.

01:01:42.570 --> 01:01:48.100
You know, I feel like a voyeur
of just this incredible ride

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:51.450
that Amanda's gone on since
she was named the finalist

01:01:51.450 --> 01:01:54.300
at the Kennedy Center to
go into the White House,

01:01:54.300 --> 01:01:57.790
to being named the Youth
Poet Laureate of the US.

01:01:57.790 --> 01:02:00.750
I watched her rap on Hot 97.

01:02:00.750 --> 01:02:05.650
I saw her on a billboard
in Times Square,

01:02:05.650 --> 01:02:09.510
making her first
presidential address, you know,

01:02:09.510 --> 01:02:13.960
20 years plus before
she'll be the president.

01:02:13.960 --> 01:02:17.670
[Laughter] And I've seen her
on so many pieces of press

01:02:17.670 --> 01:02:20.240
that we can't even keep
up as a small organization

01:02:20.240 --> 01:02:22.340
with like three or
four staff members.

01:02:22.340 --> 01:02:26.420
So tell us a little
bit about the journey,

01:02:26.420 --> 01:02:31.350
but also tell us what was --
what are some of the highlights?

01:02:31.350 --> 01:02:32.920
You don't have to name
just one because I know

01:02:32.920 --> 01:02:34.220
that would probably be hard.

01:02:34.220 --> 01:02:37.030
But what were some of your
favorite moments this past year

01:02:37.030 --> 01:02:40.580
as being the first ever
National Youth Poet Laureate?

01:02:42.500 --> 01:02:44.520
&gt;&gt; Amanda Gorman: I'm sorry,
there are so many emotions going

01:02:44.520 --> 01:02:46.440
on right now, one
feeling of like inadequacy

01:02:46.440 --> 01:02:48.100
because we have geniuses
on the panel.

01:02:48.100 --> 01:02:51.680
Like let me say something as
intellectually like powerful.

01:02:51.680 --> 01:02:54.330
Yes; I mean, it's
been a crazy ride.

01:02:54.330 --> 01:02:56.820
And when I try to explain to
people, it's not just the ride

01:02:56.820 --> 01:02:59.970
of like this year, but I think
of it as kind of voyeur journey

01:02:59.970 --> 01:03:01.670
of ever since I met
Michael Cirelli,

01:03:01.670 --> 01:03:03.550
when I was first named
LA Youth Poet Laureate,

01:03:03.550 --> 01:03:06.950
and being on that ark of not
only the growth of myself

01:03:06.950 --> 01:03:09.620
as a poet, but growing also
with us as an organization

01:03:09.620 --> 01:03:12.190
and seeing the fantastic
spread of this program,

01:03:12.190 --> 01:03:15.440
and seeing how much people
believe in the power of youth

01:03:15.440 --> 01:03:17.480
and poetry when combined.

01:03:17.480 --> 01:03:20.700
So in that regard, it's so
difficult to choose highlights.

01:03:20.700 --> 01:03:23.760
And I've kind of split them
in two; I've split them

01:03:23.760 --> 01:03:27.130
in like the half in which people
easily recognize, for example,

01:03:27.130 --> 01:03:34.690
meeting Michelle Obama like
period, dot, and new paragraph;

01:03:34.690 --> 01:03:36.480
[laughter] you know, and the
amazing things I've been able

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:38.950
to do whether it's writing
within New York Times,

01:03:38.950 --> 01:03:40.530
or being able to give a state

01:03:40.530 --> 01:03:42.620
of the union address
on MTV for 2036.

01:03:42.620 --> 01:03:46.080
I was checking my calendar,
I'm like, "You know it's not

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:49.500
that near yet, but
sure, we can do this."

01:03:49.500 --> 01:03:51.410
And so those are some
great highlights.

01:03:51.410 --> 01:03:53.770
But for me the moments
that keep me going,

01:03:53.770 --> 01:03:56.710
the moments that rejuvenate me,
and why I do my work is kind

01:03:56.710 --> 01:03:58.430
of like a lot of the moments
I think all of us have talked

01:03:58.430 --> 01:04:01.670
about on the panel, it's that
person who comes up to you

01:04:01.670 --> 01:04:03.520
after the performance
or after the reading,

01:04:03.520 --> 01:04:05.720
and tells you the story.

01:04:05.720 --> 01:04:08.300
And I mean, one of the things
that I continually deal

01:04:08.300 --> 01:04:11.320
with is growing up,
having a speed impediment,

01:04:11.320 --> 01:04:13.900
and it coming back in
moments when I'm most nervous.

01:04:13.900 --> 01:04:17.370
So you can imagine going live
on MTV is kind of a moment

01:04:17.370 --> 01:04:20.160
when I'm a bit nervous
about what I'm about to do.

01:04:20.160 --> 01:04:22.610
And, you know, trying to
make decisions of how I want

01:04:22.610 --> 01:04:25.190
to navigate that; do I want
to change the way I speak,

01:04:25.190 --> 01:04:27.260
do I want to change the way
in which I present myself?

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:30.170
And when I was named
US Youth Poet Laureate,

01:04:30.170 --> 01:04:33.930
I made conscious decision to
not erase those scars of myself,

01:04:33.930 --> 01:04:36.760
and to not erase that process
that I've had of dealing

01:04:36.760 --> 01:04:38.370
with an auditory
processing disorder,

01:04:38.370 --> 01:04:40.800
dealing with a speech
impediment while being a speaker

01:04:40.800 --> 01:04:42.100
who travels around the country.

01:04:42.100 --> 01:04:47.020
And time and time again, I will
get onstage and tell my story.

01:04:47.020 --> 01:04:48.320
And especially that --

01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:49.620
I remember that first night

01:04:49.620 --> 01:04:51.460
when I was named US
Youth Poet Laureate

01:04:51.460 --> 01:04:53.940
at Gracie Mansion there was
a girl who came up to me

01:04:53.940 --> 01:04:56.150
with her mom, and she
was like six years old,

01:04:56.150 --> 01:04:58.960
and she has these big brown
eyes, and she starts talking

01:04:58.960 --> 01:05:00.260
to me about how she has

01:05:00.260 --> 01:05:02.870
that same exact auditory
processing disorder that I have

01:05:02.870 --> 01:05:04.170
and a speech impediment.

01:05:04.170 --> 01:05:05.810
But because of me,
she's inspired

01:05:05.810 --> 01:05:07.400
to write and share her voice.

01:05:07.400 --> 01:05:09.590
And I don't think
highlights get better

01:05:09.590 --> 01:05:10.970
than that, I really don't.

01:05:10.970 --> 01:05:14.180
And it's not that I'm trying
to convert people to poets.

01:05:14.180 --> 01:05:17.010
I'm not trying to make all the
little children that I meet

01:05:17.010 --> 01:05:18.780
with become published authors.

01:05:18.780 --> 01:05:20.510
That's not my duty.

01:05:20.510 --> 01:05:26.540
But my duty is to make
them believe in themselves.

01:05:26.540 --> 01:05:29.510
And that has been t

01:05:29.510 --> 01:05:34.200
[ Applause ]

01:05:34.200 --> 01:05:36.410
&gt;&gt; Michael Cirelli: I think we
want to open up some questions.

01:05:36.410 --> 01:05:40.240
If you all have any questions,
it would be a good time

01:05:40.240 --> 01:05:41.930
to offer some of those up.

01:05:41.930 --> 01:05:44.930
It's probably not going to
be many opportunities to be

01:05:44.930 --> 01:05:47.360
with the five finalists
and their current --

01:05:47.360 --> 01:05:49.150
the first ever National
Youth Poet Laureate,

01:05:49.150 --> 01:05:51.900
so anyone have a question?

01:05:57.100 --> 01:05:58.950
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] out of curiosity
for the five finalists,

01:05:58.950 --> 01:06:00.250
what did you imagine
having access

01:06:00.250 --> 01:06:11.860
to this platform would allow
you to do, in terms of --

01:06:11.860 --> 01:06:13.270
as you all said, having your
voices heard [inaudible],

01:06:13.270 --> 01:06:22.900
I wonder how you imagine
this responsibility

01:06:22.900 --> 01:06:30.040
and this opportunity allowing
you to be a representative

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:41.400
for young people in general,
your cities, and your nation?

01:06:41.400 --> 01:06:43.160
&gt;&gt; Cassidy Martin: Okay; so --

01:06:43.160 --> 01:06:46.790
I don't know if this
is on, but that's okay.

01:06:46.790 --> 01:06:51.200
To answer that question,
that was actually one

01:06:51.200 --> 01:06:53.670
of the essay questions.

01:06:53.670 --> 01:06:59.440
We had to write an essay
saying [laughter] what --

01:06:59.440 --> 01:07:02.400
we had to write an essay saying
like, "What do we want --

01:07:02.400 --> 01:07:05.350
as a Youth Poet Laureate, what
-- it's what do you want to --

01:07:05.350 --> 01:07:07.510
basically what she said, that's
the question we were asked.

01:07:07.510 --> 01:07:10.040
[Inaudible Comment]

01:07:10.040 --> 01:07:11.740
&gt;&gt; Cassidy Martin: Oh, good,
you can read mine then,

01:07:11.740 --> 01:07:15.260
because I'm about to summarize
it for you right now, okay?

01:07:15.260 --> 01:07:16.560
&gt;&gt; Michael Pirelli:
So everybody get

01:07:16.560 --> 01:07:17.860
in on this because [inaudible].

01:07:17.860 --> 01:07:19.160
&gt;&gt; Cassidy Martin: Go
ahead, I'm not scared.

01:07:19.160 --> 01:07:26.580
Okay, look, this is what I say.

01:07:26.580 --> 01:07:30.320
[Laughter] I -- when I first
became the Youth Poet Laureate

01:07:30.320 --> 01:07:34.210
of Nashville, the first
year that I was, you know,

01:07:34.210 --> 01:07:38.170
it was very new, and so
I recognized that because

01:07:38.170 --> 01:07:41.900
of this title, I could go into
government official places

01:07:41.900 --> 01:07:46.740
with an official meaning and
reason for why I was there,

01:07:46.740 --> 01:07:49.810
and people would listen
to me because of that.

01:07:49.810 --> 01:07:54.130
But I will always defend
this statement to the death

01:07:54.130 --> 01:07:56.510
that I don't care
what title I have,

01:07:56.510 --> 01:07:59.330
I am going to be
doing the same thing

01:07:59.330 --> 01:08:01.350
that I would be doing
without that title.

01:08:01.350 --> 01:08:05.580
But the title amplifies
your voice.

01:08:05.580 --> 01:08:09.850
So the fact that this title was
created is the whole reason we

01:08:09.850 --> 01:08:12.010
even have this opportunity.

01:08:12.010 --> 01:08:14.630
But whether you have
a title or not --

01:08:14.630 --> 01:08:19.060
and this is my personal mission
, it doesn't matter who you are,

01:08:19.060 --> 01:08:25.430
it doesn't matter what your
name is, if you have a purpose,

01:08:25.430 --> 01:08:27.450
be driven and do that purpose.

01:08:27.450 --> 01:08:29.990
And it doesn't matter
what happens,

01:08:29.990 --> 01:08:31.660
or what people call you,

01:08:31.660 --> 01:08:36.110
if that's what they remember you
by, it's like Maya Angelou said,

01:08:36.110 --> 01:08:38.330
"People will not always
remember what you said,

01:08:38.330 --> 01:08:40.940
but people will always remember
how you made them feel."

01:08:40.940 --> 01:08:45.350
And that's the true mission, not
to win a title, but to get kids

01:08:45.350 --> 01:08:48.510
like us up here in the future.

01:08:48.510 --> 01:08:53.590
[ Applause ]

01:08:53.590 --> 01:08:56.970
&gt;&gt; Patricia Frazier:
Yes, all of that.

01:08:56.970 --> 01:08:59.930
[Laughter] But also for
me, I think some of it --

01:08:59.930 --> 01:09:01.530
a lot of it is personal.

01:09:01.530 --> 01:09:08.020
I've lost so many friends,
and so much of my family.

01:09:08.020 --> 01:09:10.470
And something -- and
I lost my grandma

01:09:10.470 --> 01:09:12.070
like a couple of months ago.

01:09:12.070 --> 01:09:15.520
And something that she
always made apparent to me,

01:09:15.520 --> 01:09:17.680
and apparent to everybody
was that it's so,

01:09:17.680 --> 01:09:19.470
so important to be loud.

01:09:19.470 --> 01:09:21.250
Sometimes I was embarrassed
of my voice,

01:09:21.250 --> 01:09:24.580
embarrassed of being loud, but
then I think about the fact

01:09:24.580 --> 01:09:30.120
that if I'm not writing
poems, what girl --

01:09:30.120 --> 01:09:32.220
like how are you going
to know that girls --

01:09:32.220 --> 01:09:34.730
black girls from the projects
and ghetto girls exist,

01:09:34.730 --> 01:09:37.700
and can be educated, and
can be socially-conscious

01:09:37.700 --> 01:09:39.000
and all of these things?

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:41.040
And I think that it's
really important that --

01:09:41.040 --> 01:09:44.850
like you said, all of us are
on this stage because each one

01:09:44.850 --> 01:09:48.720
of us has a certain
identity that closes a gap

01:09:48.720 --> 01:09:50.980
in the narrative of what
an American looks like.

01:09:50.980 --> 01:09:53.150
So that's why like
that's so important to me.

01:09:53.150 --> 01:09:55.490
Like you said, regardless
of the title,

01:09:55.490 --> 01:09:58.970
I'm going to be doing
the same exact thing.

01:09:58.970 --> 01:10:01.800
But I don't know, like
besides Tiffany Haddish,

01:10:01.800 --> 01:10:05.080
what like black woman who's
just belligerent, and ghetto

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:08.620
and about her people is
on platforms like this,

01:10:08.620 --> 01:10:09.920
or on platforms like this.

01:10:09.920 --> 01:10:11.440
And it's also super important
to me because I think

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:14.870
that ordinary people deserve
biographies, too, right?

01:10:14.870 --> 01:10:17.420
So often, when we write about
people, we write about people

01:10:17.420 --> 01:10:20.250
who we think like, from
a hierarchical position,

01:10:20.250 --> 01:10:22.980
and to defeat the hierarchy
of what you see going

01:10:22.980 --> 01:10:24.280
on in America right now,

01:10:24.280 --> 01:10:27.000
especially with who our
president is, and who we have

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:29.120
in office, we have to understand

01:10:29.120 --> 01:10:32.890
that sometimes we don't need
a white [inaudible] male

01:10:32.890 --> 01:10:36.590
to be the forefront, or to be
moderating the conversation,

01:10:36.590 --> 01:10:38.730
or to be the speaker
on the table.

01:10:38.730 --> 01:10:40.510
Sometimes we need a queer woman,

01:10:40.510 --> 01:10:42.960
sometimes we need queer black
women, sometimes we need --

01:10:42.960 --> 01:10:44.610
like all of us represent
a different image

01:10:44.610 --> 01:10:47.490
of what America is; and that's
why I think that regardless

01:10:47.490 --> 01:10:52.610
of who wins, I would be proud
of any one of us because all

01:10:52.610 --> 01:10:57.480
of us are not the same narrative
that you see every single day.

01:10:57.480 --> 01:11:00.270
And like I said, for me, I
just want to amplify the voices

01:11:00.270 --> 01:11:02.550
of the people that I've
lost and tell their stories.

01:11:02.550 --> 01:11:05.460
That's why so many of my poems
are not just specifically

01:11:05.460 --> 01:11:08.280
about politics, but the politics
of the people, the politics

01:11:08.280 --> 01:11:11.420
of my mom, the politics of my
Auntie Julie, and the politics

01:11:11.420 --> 01:11:13.690
of these ordinary people
who people aren't going

01:11:13.690 --> 01:11:14.990
to remember their
names, but they're going

01:11:14.990 --> 01:11:16.290
to remember their stories.

01:11:16.290 --> 01:11:19.420
And they're going to
remember, "Hey, I exist,

01:11:19.420 --> 01:11:21.660
but I have to remember I'm
in a bubble, and there are

01:11:21.660 --> 01:11:25.540
so many people out there in the
world like me who exist too,

01:11:25.540 --> 01:11:27.180
and who are human too."

01:11:27.180 --> 01:11:29.510
So yes.

01:11:29.510 --> 01:11:32.880
[ Applause ]

01:11:32.880 --> 01:11:34.180
&gt;&gt; Rumkini Kalamangalam:
Yes, definitely.

01:11:34.180 --> 01:11:38.540
I feel that because as an
Asian-American slam poet,

01:11:38.540 --> 01:11:43.190
I don't see a lot of Asian
American slam poets, you know?

01:11:43.190 --> 01:11:46.670
[Laughter] We're taught in our
communities that the best way

01:11:46.670 --> 01:11:49.740
to go unnoticed and to
get ahead is to be silent,

01:11:49.740 --> 01:11:51.590
and to let people
do what they want,

01:11:51.590 --> 01:11:53.730
and then do your thing
in the background.

01:11:53.730 --> 01:11:55.970
And I'm so tired of that
narrative defining our

01:11:55.970 --> 01:11:58.210
community, you know,
and defining who we are,

01:11:58.210 --> 01:11:59.800
and how we move up in life.

01:11:59.800 --> 01:12:03.120
It's like so many of our,
you know, images that we hold

01:12:03.120 --> 01:12:05.810
up as successful end
up turning their backs

01:12:05.810 --> 01:12:08.820
on Asian American people who
don't follow in that line,

01:12:08.820 --> 01:12:10.570
who don't want to become
doctors, who don't want

01:12:10.570 --> 01:12:14.440
to become lawyers or eng, you
know, activists and who want

01:12:14.440 --> 01:12:16.390
to stand in solidarity
with other people of color,

01:12:16.390 --> 01:12:18.430
and other marginalized
movements.

01:12:18.430 --> 01:12:21.560
And that is what is
important to me as, you know,

01:12:21.560 --> 01:12:23.390
part of this platform
is that, you know,

01:12:23.390 --> 01:12:27.380
the title of Youth Poet Laureate
of a city or a region, or,

01:12:27.380 --> 01:12:29.850
you know, a country
brings poetry

01:12:29.850 --> 01:12:31.970
to the mainstream in some sense.

01:12:31.970 --> 01:12:35.340
You know, it brings people
who are attracted by success

01:12:35.340 --> 01:12:39.030
to listen, and to listen to
what we have to say as people

01:12:39.030 --> 01:12:41.760
who are, you know, often
dismissed as alternative.

01:12:41.760 --> 01:12:46.300
And so for me, a large part of
this is inspiring other girls

01:12:46.300 --> 01:12:50.650
who -- other, you know,
Asian-American girls

01:12:50.650 --> 01:12:58.510
who didn't feel like their
voices were big enough to

01:12:58.510 --> 01:13:02.100
[ Applause ]

01:13:02.100 --> 01:13:05.010
&gt;&gt; William Lohier: And I think
I totally agree with everyone --

01:13:05.010 --> 01:13:06.310
with what everyone
else has said.

01:13:06.310 --> 01:13:07.690
And I think it's
really important to note

01:13:07.690 --> 01:13:11.440
that for every single one of
us here, there are hundreds

01:13:11.440 --> 01:13:14.010
and thousands of youth
that are not on this stage

01:13:14.010 --> 01:13:16.410
that don't have the
opportunity to be here.

01:13:16.410 --> 01:13:20.800
And so I think it's the
obligation I think that a lot

01:13:20.800 --> 01:13:23.660
of what the Youth Poet
Laureate does is public,

01:13:23.660 --> 01:13:26.300
is in front of other people,

01:13:26.300 --> 01:13:29.180
but so much of that
is behind the scenes;

01:13:29.180 --> 01:13:34.870
is working with those
organizations,

01:13:34.870 --> 01:13:39.750
is helping the youth
in their communities

01:13:39.750 --> 01:13:45.510
who don't have the kind of
platform that they have.

01:13:45.510 --> 01:13:49.390
[ Applause ]

01:13:49.390 --> 01:13:52.010
&gt;&gt; Milla Kudas: So ditto,
ditto, ditto, ditto.

01:13:52.010 --> 01:13:56.720
I also think that -- I talk
a lot about how I feel --

01:13:56.720 --> 01:13:58.020
like maybe this could be an LA,

01:13:58.020 --> 01:14:01.240
that a lot of the activism
you see sometimes is very

01:14:01.240 --> 01:14:03.840
performative in that
people will go up on a stage

01:14:03.840 --> 01:14:05.760
and do a slam poem, and
this could be my own slam

01:14:05.760 --> 01:14:07.060
team sometimes.

01:14:07.060 --> 01:14:08.360
They'll like do a poem about
like women empowerment,

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:10.650
and then after practice
will say something to me

01:14:10.650 --> 01:14:12.280
that I will not stop
thinking about for two weeks.

01:14:12.280 --> 01:14:14.150
And it will just be like
they do it for the scores,

01:14:14.150 --> 01:14:15.610
but they don't really do
it in their communities;

01:14:15.610 --> 01:14:17.050
they don't really communicate
with the people around them.

01:14:17.050 --> 01:14:20.220
And so my mission is
to create poetry spaces

01:14:20.220 --> 01:14:23.150
that are both accessible, and
also are held accountable,

01:14:23.150 --> 01:14:25.290
in that I want to
see more people --

01:14:25.290 --> 01:14:26.590
like we were talking about,

01:14:26.590 --> 01:14:27.890
we all represent a different
narrative, but there are

01:14:27.890 --> 01:14:29.290
so many more narratives still.

01:14:29.290 --> 01:14:30.700
And I want to invite
those narratives

01:14:30.700 --> 01:14:32.090
to the stage to speak as well.

01:14:32.090 --> 01:14:33.840
And then I think in
terms of creating

01:14:33.840 --> 01:14:36.120
like a tangible change is like
when you're given a platform

01:14:36.120 --> 01:14:38.210
like that like share
a GoFundMe page.

01:14:38.210 --> 01:14:40.710
Like get conversations
circulating

01:14:40.710 --> 01:14:44.680
so that we can start a grander
discussion than just my voice.

01:14:44.680 --> 01:14:47.410
And then outside of that,
I'm also really gay.

01:14:47.410 --> 01:14:52.050
[Laughter] And I want to do --
I identify as fem non-binary,

01:14:52.050 --> 01:14:53.940
and I feel like a lot of times,

01:14:53.940 --> 01:14:56.720
I have to like tame this
non-binary part of myself,

01:14:56.720 --> 01:15:00.170
and like kind of silence
the whole gender exploration

01:15:00.170 --> 01:15:01.840
that is going on in my brain.

01:15:01.840 --> 01:15:04.890
And I want to not only be a
role model for other people

01:15:04.890 --> 01:15:07.060
who are just as confused
about their gender as I am,

01:15:07.060 --> 01:15:12.970
but also learn from other people
and be able to create these com,

01:15:12.970 --> 01:15:17.750
and rather I feel empowered to
be as much as myself as I can be

01:15:17.750 --> 01:15:19.910
so that I know that other
people feel that same way.

01:15:19.910 --> 01:15:21.210
So yes. [Laughter]

01:15:21.210 --> 01:15:22.510
&gt;&gt; Cassidy Martin: Also,

01:15:22.510 --> 01:15:26.600
[applause] like one more thing
-- I want to say one more thing.

01:15:26.600 --> 01:15:29.500
I think I can speak for all
five of us, all six of us,

01:15:29.500 --> 01:15:33.600
all seven of us to say that
like just because we're up here,

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:37.910
we have a title, the real work
isn't just getting upon stage

01:15:37.910 --> 01:15:41.410
or standing up at Library of
Congress and spitting a poem.

01:15:41.410 --> 01:15:45.770
It's actually going,
and teaching them.

01:15:45.770 --> 01:15:48.660
The work that is combined
just from five of us

01:15:48.660 --> 01:15:52.470
up here is a whole -- is a
year's worth of blood, sweat,

01:15:52.470 --> 01:15:56.250
and tears from teenagers,
from college students,

01:15:56.250 --> 01:15:59.130
who actually go in the community
and do things besides get

01:15:59.130 --> 01:16:00.550
up on stage and write poems.

01:16:00.550 --> 01:16:02.960
We help kids write
their own poems.

01:16:02.960 --> 01:16:05.500
And that is what's important,
and that is the mission.

01:16:05.500 --> 01:16:06.800
[Applause]

